<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<title>alamo-benchmarking — fleet report</title>
<style>
  :root {
    --fg: #1a1a1a;
    --muted: #555;
    --bg: #ffffff;
    --border: #d0d0d0;
    --row-alt: #f7f7f7;
    --warn: #b35900;
    --bad: #b3001b;
    --ok: #2a7a2a;
  }
  body {
    font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", Roboto, sans-serif;
    color: var(--fg);
    background: var(--bg);
    margin: 0;
    padding: 1.5rem 2rem 4rem;
    line-height: 1.45;
    max-width: 1280px;
  }
  h1 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin: 0 0 0.4rem 0; }
  h2 { margin-top: 2.4rem; font-size: 1.4rem; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border); padding-bottom: 0.2rem; }
  h3 { margin-top: 1.6rem; font-size: 1.05rem; color: var(--muted); }
  p, ul { color: var(--fg); }
  .lede { color: var(--muted); font-size: 0.95rem; }
  table {
    border-collapse: collapse;
    margin: 0.6rem 0 1rem 0;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    width: 100%;
  }
  th, td {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding: 0.3rem 0.55rem;
    text-align: left;
    vertical-align: top;
  }
  th { background: #efefef; }
  tr:nth-child(even) td { background: var(--row-alt); }
  td.num, th.num { text-align: right; font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums; }
  td.mono, th.mono { font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace; font-size: 0.8rem; }
  figure { margin: 0 0 1.4rem 0; }
  figure img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }
  figcaption { color: var(--muted); font-size: 0.85rem; padding: 0.2rem 0 0 0; }
  .section-desc { color: var(--muted); margin: 0.2rem 0 0.6rem 0; }
  .footnote { color: var(--muted); font-size: 0.82rem; border-top: 1px dashed var(--border); padding-top: 0.4rem; margin-top: 0.5rem; }
  .pill { display: inline-block; padding: 0.05rem 0.4rem; border-radius: 0.6rem; background: #e8e8e8; color: #333; font-size: 0.75rem; }
  .pill.warn { background: #fde8d3; color: var(--warn); }
  .pill.bad { background: #fde0e3; color: var(--bad); }
  .pill.ok { background: #def0de; color: var(--ok); }
  .machine-block { margin: 1.2rem 0; padding: 0.6rem 0.8rem; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 6px; background: #fafafa; }
  .machine-block h3 { margin-top: 0; }
  details { margin: 0.6rem 0; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 4px; padding: 0.3rem 0.6rem; background: #fbfbfb; }
  details > summary { cursor: pointer; color: var(--muted); padding: 0.15rem 0; user-select: none; }
  details[open] > summary { color: var(--fg); font-weight: 500; border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--border); margin-bottom: 0.4rem; }
  code { background: #f0f0f0; padding: 0 0.2rem; border-radius: 3px; }
  nav.toc { font-size: 0.9rem; }
  nav.toc ol { padding-left: 1.2rem; }
  .tabbar { display: flex; gap: 0.3rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin: 0.4rem 0 0.6rem 0; }
  .tabbar button {
    font: inherit;
    color: var(--muted);
    background: #f0f0f0;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 4px;
    padding: 0.25rem 0.65rem;
    cursor: pointer;
  }
  .tabbar button.active {
    color: var(--fg);
    background: #fff;
    border-color: #777;
    box-shadow: 0 1px 0 #777 inset;
  }
  .tab-panel { display: none; }
  .tab-panel.active { display: block; }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>alamo-benchmarking — fleet report</h1>
<p class="lede">Generated {{ generated_at }} · {{ machine_ids|length }} machine(s): {{ machine_ids|join(", ") }}</p>

<p class="lede">
  Machines are ordered <strong>slowest &rarr; fastest</strong> (left to right in
  combined plots, top to bottom in per-machine sections) by their best
  measured SCP elastic wall time, so every figure tells the same story in the
  same direction. Raw per-machine tables are folded into expandable
  drop-downs.
</p>

<nav class="toc">
<ol>
  <li><a href="#inventory">Run inventory</a></li>
  <li><a href="#tool-versions">Tool versions per machine</a></li>
  <li><a href="#preflight">Pre-flight outcomes</a></li>
  <li><a href="#noise-floor">Noise floor</a></li>
  <li><a href="#compile">Compile benchmarks</a></li>
  <li><a href="#regression">Regression suite</a></li>
  <li><a href="#scp-optimal">SCP elastic — best per-machine wall time</a></li>
  <li><a href="#geekbench">SCP elastic vs Geekbench prediction</a></li>
  <li><a href="#scp">SCP elastic — strong scaling sweep</a></li>
  <li><a href="#scp-determinism">SCP output-hash determinism</a></li>
  <li><a href="#render-frames">Render frames</a></li>
  <li><a href="#render-encode">Render encode by codec</a></li>
  <li><a href="#power-util">Combined telemetry: power and utilization</a></li>
  <li><a href="#telemetry">Telemetry overview</a></li>
  <li><a href="#telemetry-zoom">Telemetry zoom: SCP optimal-np rep</a></li>
  <li><a href="#telemetry-summary">Telemetry summary per benchmark</a></li>
  <li><a href="#appendix">Appendix — raw data locations</a></li>
</ol>
</nav>

<h2 id="inventory">1. Run inventory</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  One row per machine. <code>machine_id</code> is the lab-stable identifier
  declared by the operator (SETUP.md §4b); <code>hostname</code> is the OS
  hostname captured at run time. Wall duration is the end-to-end run length —
  <code>started_at</code> to <code>ended_at</code>, including all cooldowns.
  Repo SHAs marked with a <span class="pill warn">dirty</span> pill had
  uncommitted changes when the run started.
</p>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>machine_id</th>
      <th>hostname</th>
      <th>OS</th>
      <th>CPU</th>
      <th class="num">phys / virt</th>
      <th class="num">RAM (GB)</th>
      <th>started (UTC)</th>
      <th class="num">duration</th>
      <th>benchmark SHA</th>
      <th>alamo SHA</th>
      <th>config mode</th>
      <th class="num">schema</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for r in inventory %}
    <tr>
      <td class="mono">{{ r.machine_id }}</td>
      <td class="mono">{{ r.hostname }}</td>
      <td>{{ r.os }}</td>
      <td>{{ r.cpu }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.cores_physical }} / {{ r.cores_virtual }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ "%.1f"|format(r.ram_gb) }}</td>
      <td class="mono">{{ r.started_at|fmt_dt }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.duration_seconds|fmt_dur }}</td>
      <td class="mono">{{ (r.benchmark_sha or "—")[:10] }}{% if r.benchmark_dirty %} <span class="pill warn">dirty</span>{% endif %}</td>
      <td class="mono">{{ (r.alamo_sha or "—")[:10] }}{% if r.alamo_dirty %} <span class="pill warn">dirty</span>{% endif %}</td>
      <td>{{ r.config_mode }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.schema_version }}</td>
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2 id="tool-versions">2. Tool versions</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  Exact versions of every tool involved in benchmarking, captured by
  <code>platform_info.collect</code> at run time. The compiler is the
  per-OS vanilla toolchain: Apple Clang on macOS, LLVM clang on Linux --
  both invoked via <code>$PATH</code> as <code>clang++</code>.
</p>
<details>
  <summary>Raw data: per-machine tool-version matrix</summary>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>tool</th>
        {% for m in machine_ids %}<th>{{ m }}</th>{% endfor %}
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
    {% for tool in tool_keys %}
      <tr>
        <td class="mono">{{ tool }}</td>
        {% for b in bundles %}
          <td class="mono">{{ b.host.tool_versions.get(tool, "—") }}</td>
        {% endfor %}
      </tr>
    {% endfor %}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</details>

<h2 id="preflight">3. Pre-flight outcomes</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  Every pre-flight check the benchmark performed before allowing the run.
  Severity <code>required</code> aborts the run if it fails;
  <code>advisory</code> is recorded but does not block.
  <code>n/a</code> means the check doesn't apply to this OS (e.g.
  <code>rapl_pl1</code> is Linux-only; <code>cpu_governor</code> is mode-only on macOS).
</p>
{% for pre in preflight_rows %}
  <details>
    <summary>{{ pre.machine_id }} -- overall <span class="pill {% if pre.passed %}ok{% else %}bad{% endif %}">{{ "PASS" if pre.passed else "FAIL" }}</span></summary>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>check</th><th>observed</th><th>required</th><th>severity</th><th>passed</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
      {% for c in pre.checks %}
        <tr>
          <td class="mono">{{ c.name }}</td>
          <td class="mono">{{ c.observed }}</td>
          <td class="mono">{{ c.required }}</td>
          <td>{{ c.severity }}</td>
          <td>{% if c.passed %}<span class="pill ok">yes</span>{% else %}<span class="pill bad">no</span>{% endif %}</td>
        </tr>
      {% endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </details>
{% endfor %}

<h2 id="noise-floor">4. Noise floor</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  Twenty repetitions of a tight 4000x4000 numpy <code>matmul</code>; the
  first rep is the warmup (excluded). This establishes the per-machine
  per-night variance baseline that the other timings should be compared
  against. Lower median = faster BLAS; smaller IQR = more stable machine.
  Use the tab bar to switch between the cross-machine box plot and a
  zoomed per-machine view (where each machine's y-axis is autoscaled to its
  own data range so the within-machine variance is visible).
</p>
<div class="tabbar" data-tabgroup="noise-floor">
  <button class="active" data-target="nf-overall">Overall</button>
  {% for tab in noise_floor_tabs %}
    <button data-target="nf-{{ loop.index }}">{{ tab.machine_id }}</button>
  {% endfor %}
</div>
<div id="nf-overall" class="tab-panel active" data-tabgroup="noise-floor">
  <figure>
    <img src="{{ figs.noise_floor }}" alt="Noise floor box plot">
    <figcaption>Box: Q1-Q3 (IQR), line: median, whiskers: full min/max range. Each machine's box represents its 19 measured reps. Machines ordered slowest -&gt; fastest by best SCP wall.</figcaption>
  </figure>
</div>
{% for tab in noise_floor_tabs %}
  <div id="nf-{{ loop.index }}" class="tab-panel" data-tabgroup="noise-floor">
    {% if tab.fig %}
      <figure>
        <img src="{{ tab.fig }}" alt="Noise floor strip for {{ tab.machine_id }}">
        <figcaption>{{ tab.machine_id }} -- 19 measured reps in measurement order. Dashed line = median; shaded band = IQR.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    {% else %}
      <p>No noise_floor data for {{ tab.machine_id }}.</p>
    {% endif %}
  </div>
{% endfor %}
<details>
  <summary>Raw data: noise-floor summary table</summary>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>machine</th><th class="num">n</th><th class="num">median (s)</th><th class="num">IQR (s)</th><th class="num">min (s)</th><th class="num">max (s)</th><th class="num">stdev (s)</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
    {% for r in noise_floor_table %}
      <tr>
        <td class="mono">{{ r.machine_id }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.n }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.median_s|fmt_float(4) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.iqr_s|fmt_float(4) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.min_s|fmt_float(4) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.max_s|fmt_float(4) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.stdev_s|fmt_float(4) }}</td>
      </tr>
    {% endfor %}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</details>

<h2 id="compile">5. Compile benchmarks</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  Cold-cache Alamo build, all configured dims (default: 2D + 3D) per rep.
  <code>compile_serial</code> uses <code>make -j1</code>;
  <code>compile_parallel</code> uses <code>make -j&lt;physical&gt;</code>.
  Before each rep, the alamo submodule is wiped with <code>git clean -fdx -e .venv</code> +
  <code>git checkout -- .</code>, and <code>CCACHE_DISABLE=1</code> is set.
  Reps per benchmark: 2 measured + 1 warmup.
</p>
<figure>
  <img src="{{ figs.compile }}" alt="Compile wall-time bars">
  <figcaption>Median wall time per benchmark; error bars span Q1–Q3 (IQR) over the 2 measured reps.</figcaption>
</figure>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>machine</th>
      <th class="num">serial median (s)</th>
      <th class="num">serial IQR (s)</th>
      <th class="num">parallel j</th>
      <th class="num">parallel median (s)</th>
      <th class="num">parallel IQR (s)</th>
      <th class="num">speedup (serial / parallel)</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for r in compile_table %}
    <tr>
      <td class="mono">{{ r.machine_id }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.serial_median_s|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.serial_iqr_s|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.j or "—" }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.parallel_median_s|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.parallel_iqr_s|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.speedup|fmt_float(2) }}×</td>
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2 id="regression">6. Regression suite</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  Alamo's regression suite invoked via
  <code>./scripts/runtests.py --comp clang++</code>; reps per benchmark:
  2 measured + 1 warmup. {% if regression_skip_count %}{{ regression_skip_count }} test
  section(s) are deliberately skipped on every machine for fairness — some
  sections are known to fail erroneously on macOS (e.g. Voronoi /
  ThermoElastic 2D tolerance issues), so they are skipped uniformly across
  the fleet to keep the cross-platform comparison apples-to-apples. The
  configured skip list is identical on every machine and is recorded under
  <code>config.benchmarks.regression.skip_tests</code> in each run's
  manifest. The skip directive is honored by <code>runtests.py</code> and
  the skipped sections are reported in the per-rep notes column.{% endif %}
</p>
<figure>
  <img src="{{ figs.regression }}" alt="Regression suite walls">
  <figcaption>Per-rep walls (scatter, colored per machine) over the median bar (IQR error bars).</figcaption>
</figure>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>machine</th><th class="num">n</th><th class="num">median (s)</th><th class="num">IQR (s)</th><th class="num">min (s)</th><th class="num">max (s)</th><th>notes</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for r in regression_table %}
    <tr>
      <td class="mono">{{ r.machine_id }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.n }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.median_s|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.iqr_s|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.min_s|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.max_s|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
      <td>{{ r.notes }}</td>
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2 id="scp-optimal">7. SCP elastic -- best per-machine wall time</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  For each machine: the <code>np</code> value with the lowest median measured wall
  time, presented in linear seconds for direct comparison. Each bar is labeled
  on two lines: the optimal <code>np</code> on top, and the wall multiplier
  relative to the fastest machine on the second line (e.g. <code>4.13x</code> =
  "4.13 times slower than the fastest machine's best wall"). The fastest
  machine reads <code>baseline</code>. Error bars are IQR over the 5 reps at
  the optimal <code>np</code>. This is the metric used to order machines
  throughout the report.
</p>
<figure>
  <img src="{{ figs.scp_optimal }}" alt="SCP optimal-np wall time per machine">
  <figcaption>Median wall time at each machine's optimal <code>np</code>. Linear y-axis. Order: slowest left, fastest right. Annotation: optimal <code>np</code> and slowdown multiplier vs the fastest machine.</figcaption>
</figure>
<details>
  <summary>Raw data: optimal-np summary table</summary>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>machine</th>
        <th class="num">optimal np</th>
        <th class="num">reps</th>
        <th class="num">median (s)</th>
        <th class="num">IQR (s)</th>
        <th class="num">min (s)</th>
        <th class="num">max (s)</th>
        <th class="num">multiplier vs fastest</th>
        <th class="num">% slower than fastest</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
    {% for r in scp_optimal_table %}
      <tr>
        <td class="mono">{{ r.machine_id }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.optimal_np or "—" }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.reps }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.median_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.iqr_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.min_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.max_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.multiplier|fmt_float(2) }}x</td>
        <td class="num">{% if r.pct_slower is not none %}+{{ r.pct_slower|fmt_float(1) }}%{% else %}—{% endif %}</td>
      </tr>
    {% endfor %}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</details>

<h2 id="geekbench">8. SCP elastic vs Geekbench prediction</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  Geekbench 6 scores for each lab machine (operator-supplied, source-of-truth
  in <code>benchmarks/report/geekbench.toml</code>) are joined against each
  machine's measured SCP optimal-np median wall. A least-squares linear
  regression in log space (<code>log(wall) = slope * log(score) + intercept</code>)
  is fit separately to single-core and multi-core scores; both fits and their
  R<sup>2</sup> are shown.
  Machines listed under <code>[prospective]</code> in the TOML are evaluated
  against the fit and shown as red star markers with their predicted SCP wall.
</p>
<figure>
  <img src="{{ figs.geekbench }}" alt="SCP wall vs Geekbench score with prospective predictions">
  <figcaption>
    Log-log scatter, one panel per Geekbench axis. Filled circles = measured
    machines, dashed line = fit, red star = prospective machine with
    predicted SCP wall from the fit. Legend shows slope and R<sup>2</sup>
    (1.0 = perfect fit; ~-1 slope ~ "wall is inversely proportional to
    Geekbench score").
  </figcaption>
</figure>

<h3>Fit summary</h3>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>axis</th>
      <th class="num">n</th>
      <th class="num">slope</th>
      <th class="num">intercept</th>
      <th class="num">R<sup>2</sup></th>
      <th class="num">score range</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for axis in ["single", "multi"] %}
    {% set fit = geekbench_fits[axis] %}
    <tr>
      <td class="mono">{{ axis }}-core</td>
      {% if fit %}
        <td class="num">{{ fit.n }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ fit.slope|fmt_float(3) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ fit.intercept|fmt_float(3) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ fit.r_squared|fmt_float(3) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ fit.score_min|fmt_float(0) }} -- {{ fit.score_max|fmt_float(0) }}</td>
      {% else %}
        <td class="num" colspan="5">insufficient data (need >= 2 known points)</td>
      {% endif %}
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Prospective-machine predictions</h3>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>cpu</th>
      <th class="num">single-core score</th>
      <th class="num">multi-core score</th>
      <th class="num">predicted wall (single fit)</th>
      <th class="num">predicted wall (multi fit)</th>
      <th>notes</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for r in geekbench_prospective %}
    <tr>
      <td class="mono">{{ r.cpu_label }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.single_core|fmt_float(0) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.multi_core|fmt_float(0) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.predicted_from_single_s|fmt_float(2) }} s</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.predicted_from_multi_s|fmt_float(2) }} s</td>
      <td>{{ r.notes }}</td>
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>

<details>
  <summary>Raw data: known machines, actual vs predicted</summary>
  <p class="section-desc">
    For every machine that has both a measured SCP wall and a Geekbench score:
    actual wall and what each fit would have predicted. The residual columns
    are <code>(actual - predicted) / predicted * 100%</code>; a positive
    number means this machine was slower than the fit expected; negative
    means faster.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>machine</th>
        <th>cpu</th>
        <th class="num">single-core</th>
        <th class="num">multi-core</th>
        <th class="num">actual wall (s)</th>
        <th class="num">predicted (single fit)</th>
        <th class="num">residual (single)</th>
        <th class="num">predicted (multi fit)</th>
        <th class="num">residual (multi)</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
    {% for r in geekbench_known %}
      <tr>
        <td class="mono">{{ r.machine_id }}</td>
        <td class="mono">{{ r.cpu_label }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.single_core|fmt_float(0) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.multi_core|fmt_float(0) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.actual_wall_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.predicted_from_single_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{% if r.residual_single_pct is not none %}{% if r.residual_single_pct >= 0 %}+{% endif %}{{ r.residual_single_pct|fmt_float(1) }}%{% else %}—{% endif %}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.predicted_from_multi_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{% if r.residual_multi_pct is not none %}{% if r.residual_multi_pct >= 0 %}+{% endif %}{{ r.residual_multi_pct|fmt_float(1) }}%{% else %}—{% endif %}</td>
      </tr>
    {% endfor %}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</details>

<h2 id="scp">9. SCP elastic -- strong-scaling sweep</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  <code>tests/SCPSpheresElastic/input</code> in 2D, <code>stop_time = 0.015s</code>.
  Each machine sweeps <code>-np</code> over <code>1, 2, 4, 8, ..., physical, physical + virtual</code>
  (de-duplicated). Reps per <code>np</code>: 5 measured + 1 warmup. Within a sweep, the run order is shuffled per
  <code>random_seed</code> in the run config to defeat slow drift correlated with rep position.
</p>
<figure>
  <img src="{{ figs.scp_wall }}" alt="SCP wall time vs np">
  <figcaption>Median wall time vs MPI ranks (log-log). Error bars are IQR over the 5 measured reps per <code>np</code>. Legend ordered slowest -&gt; fastest by best wall.</figcaption>
</figure>
<figure>
  <img src="{{ figs.scp_speedup }}" alt="SCP speedup">
  <figcaption>Speedup = T(np_0) / T(np) where np_0 is each machine's smallest np. Dashed line: ideal linear scaling.</figcaption>
</figure>
<figure>
  <img src="{{ figs.scp_efficiency }}" alt="SCP efficiency">
  <figcaption>Parallel efficiency = speedup / np. Dashed line at 1.0 = ideal.</figcaption>
</figure>

{% for table in scp_sweep_tables %}
  <details>
    <summary>Raw data: SCP sweep -- {{ table.machine_id }}</summary>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th class="num">np</th><th class="num">reps</th><th class="num">median (s)</th><th class="num">IQR (s)</th><th class="num">min (s)</th><th class="num">max (s)</th><th class="num">stdev (s)</th><th class="num">speedup vs base np</th><th class="num">efficiency</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
      {% for r in table.rows %}
        <tr>
          <td class="num">{{ r.np }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.reps }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.median_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.iqr_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.min_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.max_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.stdev_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.speedup|fmt_float(2) }}x</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.efficiency|fmt_pct }}</td>
        </tr>
      {% endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <figure>
      <img src="{{ per_machine[table.machine_id].scp_strip }}" alt="SCP per-rep walls for {{ table.machine_id }}">
      <figcaption>Per-rep wall time at each <code>np</code> for {{ table.machine_id }}; black tick is the median.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </details>
{% endfor %}

<h2 id="scp-determinism">10. SCP output-hash determinism</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  Each SCP rep records a decomposition-invariant SHA-256 over the final
  cell plotfile (per-field counts + min/max quantized to 4 sig figs).
  Two reps at the same <code>np</code> producing different hashes means
  the run is not bit-deterministic on that machine. Hashes are presented
  raw without further commentary; the first 12 hex characters per distinct
  hash are shown.
</p>
{% for table in scp_hash_tables %}
  <details>
    <summary>{{ table.machine_id }} -- distinct-hash counts per np</summary>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th class="num">np</th><th class="num">reps</th><th class="num">distinct hashes</th><th>hash prefixes</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
      {% for r in table.rows %}
        <tr>
          <td class="num">{{ r.np }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.reps }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.distinct }}</td>
          <td class="mono">{{ r.hashes|join(", ") }}</td>
        </tr>
      {% endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </details>
{% endfor %}

<h2 id="render-frames">11. Render frames</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  <code>render_frames</code> uses yt's <code>SlicePlot</code> to render one
  PNG per Alamo plotfile (the <code>eta</code> field as a z-slice, at the
  configured resolution; default <code>1920×1080</code>). Reps per benchmark:
  5 measured + 1 warmup. Input is the latest <code>scp_elastic</code> output
  plotfile directory, so the input volume scales with each machine's largest-<code>np</code>
  SCP output.
</p>
<figure>
  <img src="{{ figs.render_frames }}" alt="render_frames bars">
  <figcaption>Per-rep walls scatter over median bar (IQR error bars).</figcaption>
</figure>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>machine</th><th class="num">n</th><th class="num">median (s)</th><th class="num">IQR (s)</th><th class="num">min (s)</th><th class="num">max (s)</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for r in render_frames_table %}
    <tr>
      <td class="mono">{{ r.machine_id }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.n }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.median_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.iqr_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.min_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ r.max_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2 id="render-encode">12. Render encode by codec</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  Encoding the same rendered frame set with three codecs:
  <code>gifski</code>, <code>libx265</code>, and <code>libsvtav1</code>.
  Reps per (codec, machine): 5 measured + 1 warmup. The ffmpeg invocation
  for x265/av1 includes a <code>pad=ceil(iw/2)*2:ceil(ih/2)*2</code> filter
  to handle odd-dimension borders that <code>yuv420p</code> rejects.
</p>
<figure>
  <img src="{{ figs.render_encode }}" alt="render_encode grouped bars">
  <figcaption>Each codec along x; each machine has its own colored bar. Error bars: IQR.</figcaption>
</figure>
{% for table in render_encode_table %}
  <details>
    <summary>{{ table.machine_id }} -- per-codec encode walls</summary>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>codec</th><th class="num">n</th><th class="num">median (s)</th><th class="num">IQR (s)</th><th class="num">min (s)</th><th class="num">max (s)</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
      {% for r in table.rows %}
        <tr>
          <td class="mono">{{ r.codec }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.n }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.median_s|fmt_float(3) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.iqr_s|fmt_float(3) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.min_s|fmt_float(3) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ r.max_s|fmt_float(3) }}</td>
        </tr>
      {% endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </details>
{% endfor %}

<h2 id="power-util">13. Combined telemetry: power and utilization</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  Cross-machine views derived from 1 Hz telemetry. The power plot uses the
  full run (entry to exit, including all cooldowns); the utilization plot
  is restricted to the time windows of each machine's optimal-np SCP reps.
  Machines ordered slowest -&gt; fastest by best SCP wall.
  {% if power_compare_missing %}
  Machines missing <code>package_power_w</code> samples were excluded
  from the power plot: {{ power_compare_missing|join(", ") }}.
  {% endif %}
  {% if optimal_util_missing %}
  Machines missing per-core <code>util_pct</code> were excluded
  from the utilization plot: {{ optimal_util_missing|join(", ") }}.
  {% endif %}
</p>
<figure>
  <img src="{{ figs.power_compare }}" alt="Average and peak package power per machine">
  <figcaption>Per-machine average and peak package power (W) over the full run. Numbers above each bar are the rounded value.</figcaption>
</figure>
<figure>
  <img src="{{ figs.optimal_util }}" alt="Average per-core utilization during optimal SCP">
  <figcaption>
    Average per-core <code>util_pct</code> across every 1 Hz sample that falls
    inside any measured SCP rep at each machine's optimal <code>np</code>.
    Idle cores are included in the average -- e.g. on a 24-core box running
    np=12, half the cores read ~0% util and pull the mean toward 50%.
    Sub-label under each bar shows the optimal np and the machine's
    (physical + virtual) core counts.
  </figcaption>
</figure>
<details>
  <summary>Raw data: combined telemetry table</summary>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>machine</th>
        <th class="num">phys / virt</th>
        <th class="num">optimal np</th>
        <th class="num">optimal wall (s)</th>
        <th class="num">avg power (W)</th>
        <th class="num">peak power (W)</th>
        <th class="num">avg per-core util at optimal (%)</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
    {% for r in telemetry_combined_table %}
      <tr>
        <td class="mono">{{ r.machine_id }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.cores_physical }} / {{ r.cores_virtual }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.optimal_np or "—" }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.optimal_wall_s|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.avg_power_w|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.peak_power_w|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.avg_util_optimal_pct|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
      </tr>
    {% endfor %}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</details>

<h2 id="telemetry">14. Telemetry overview</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  1 Hz hardware telemetry for the entire run, sourced from
  <code>powermetrics --format plist</code> on macOS and
  <code>turbostat --quiet</code> on Linux. Each machine's row of plots covers
  the full <code>started_at</code>–<code>ended_at</code> window of its run;
  vertical shaded bands mark the time range during which each benchmark
  executed (band color → benchmark; see legend below).
</p>
<p class="section-desc">
  <strong>Benchmark band legend:</strong>
  noise_floor, compile_serial, compile_parallel, regression_suite,
  scp_elastic, render_frames, render_encode — bands appear in the order
  the benchmarks ran. Channels not collected on a given OS are skipped
  silently and listed at the end of this section.
</p>
{% for b in bundles %}
  <div class="machine-block">
    <h3>{{ b.run.machine_id }} — {{ b.host.cpu_brand }}</h3>
    {% set pm = per_machine[b.run.machine_id] %}
    {% if pm.package_power_w %}<figure><img src="{{ pm.package_power_w }}" alt="{{ b.run.machine_id }} power"><figcaption>Package power (W). Downsampled to ≤1500 bins by median per bin.</figcaption></figure>{% endif %}
    {% if pm.cpu_freq_avg_mhz %}<figure><img src="{{ pm.cpu_freq_avg_mhz }}" alt="{{ b.run.machine_id }} freq"><figcaption>Average and max core frequency (MHz). Downsampled to ≤1500 bins by median per bin.</figcaption></figure>{% endif %}
    {% if pm.pkg_temp_c %}<figure><img src="{{ pm.pkg_temp_c }}" alt="{{ b.run.machine_id }} temp"><figcaption>Package temperature (°C). Downsampled to ≤1500 bins by median per bin.</figcaption></figure>{% endif %}
    {% if pm.per_core_freq %}<figure><img src="{{ pm.per_core_freq }}" alt="{{ b.run.machine_id }} per-core freq"><figcaption>Per-core frequency heatmap. Cores grouped by type along Y (performance/super first, efficiency/virtual second).</figcaption></figure>{% endif %}
    {% if pm.per_core_util %}<figure><img src="{{ pm.per_core_util }}" alt="{{ b.run.machine_id }} per-core util"><figcaption>Per-core utilization heatmap (0–100%).</figcaption></figure>{% endif %}
    {% if pm.per_core_temp %}<figure><img src="{{ pm.per_core_temp }}" alt="{{ b.run.machine_id }} per-core temp"><figcaption>Per-core temperature heatmap. Linux/turbostat-only; cells are blank where the source did not report a temp.</figcaption></figure>{% endif %}
  </div>
{% endfor %}

<h3>Channels with no data</h3>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>machine</th><th>missing telemetry channels</th><th class="num">samples</th><th class="num">per-core samples</th><th class="num">timestamp offset applied (s)</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
  {% for c in telemetry_channels %}
    {% set missing = c.channels.items()|selectattr("1", "equalto", false)|map(attribute=0)|list %}
    <tr>
      <td class="mono">{{ c.machine_id }}</td>
      <td class="mono">{{ missing|join(", ") if missing else "—" }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ c.n_samples }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ c.n_per_core_samples }}</td>
      <td class="num">{{ "%.0f"|format(c.telemetry_offset_seconds) }}</td>
    </tr>
  {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
{% if macos_offset_machines %}
<p class="footnote">
  Methodology note on timestamp alignment: telemetry samples on
  {{ macos_offset_machines|join(", ") }} were captured by
  <code>powermetrics --format plist</code> whose timestamps are emitted in
  local wall-clock labeled as UTC. To align them with the result-table
  windows (which are recorded in true UTC by the runner), a fixed offset
  rounded to the nearest minute was subtracted from every telemetry sample
  on those machines; the offset is the column "timestamp offset applied"
  above.
</p>
{% endif %}

<h2 id="telemetry-zoom">15. Telemetry zoom: SCP optimal-np rep</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  Per-machine, the per-core frequency time series during the optimal-<code>np</code>
  SCP rep -- the rep that contributed to the machine's best-wall row in the
  optimal-np section above. (Within the optimal-np bucket, the longest-walling
  measured rep is shown so the time series is as wide as possible.) Useful for
  inspecting whether all cores were pinned at high frequency throughout the
  rep, or whether the OS scheduler migrated work across the perf/eff (or
  physical/virtual) split. Where <code>turbostat</code> captured a package
  temperature (Linux only), it is overlaid on a right-hand y-axis as a dashed
  red line; <code>powermetrics</code> on macOS does not surface a package-temp
  channel, so those plots show frequency only.
</p>
{% for b in bundles %}
  {% set pm = per_machine[b.run.machine_id] %}
  {% if pm.scp_zoom_freq %}
  <figure>
    <img src="{{ pm.scp_zoom_freq }}" alt="{{ b.run.machine_id }} SCP zoom">
    <figcaption>{{ b.run.machine_id }} -- per-core MHz during optimal-np SCP rep.</figcaption>
  </figure>
  {% endif %}
{% endfor %}

<h2 id="telemetry-summary">16. Telemetry summary per benchmark</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  For each benchmark on each machine, samples are joined to the
  benchmark's start–end window (first measured rep start to last measured
  rep end). Median package power, p95 of average and max core frequency,
  p95 of package and per-core temperature, and median per-core
  utilization are reported. <code>—</code> means the channel had no samples
  on that platform; <code>0</code> means there were no samples in the
  window (e.g. the run lasted less than one telemetry tick).
</p>
{% for row in telemetry_table %}
  <details>
    <summary>{{ row.machine_id }} -- per-benchmark telemetry summary</summary>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>benchmark</th>
          <th class="num">samples</th>
          <th class="num">median power (W)</th>
          <th class="num">p95 avg freq (MHz)</th>
          <th class="num">p95 max freq (MHz)</th>
          <th class="num">p95 pkg temp (&deg;C)</th>
          <th class="num">p95 core temp (&deg;C)</th>
          <th class="num">median per-core util (%)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
      {% for bench in row.benchmarks %}
        <tr>
          <td class="mono">{{ bench.benchmark }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ bench.samples }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ bench.median_power_w|fmt_float(2) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ bench.p95_freq_mhz|fmt_float(0) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ bench.p95_max_freq_mhz|fmt_float(0) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ bench.p95_pkg_temp_c|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ bench.p95_core_temp_c|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
          <td class="num">{{ bench.median_util_pct|fmt_float(1) }}</td>
        </tr>
      {% endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </details>
{% endfor %}

<h2 id="appendix">17. Appendix -- raw data locations</h2>
<p class="section-desc">
  Where each machine's run lives in the repo and how big it is. Open any
  <code>*.db</code> with <code>sqlite3</code> for ad-hoc queries (the
  schema is documented in README.md "Data model").
</p>
<details>
  <summary>Raw data: per-machine file paths and row counts</summary>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>machine</th>
        <th>run_dir (relative)</th>
        <th>db file</th>
        <th class="num">db size</th>
        <th class="num">result rows</th>
        <th class="num">telemetry samples</th>
        <th class="num">per-core samples</th>
        <th class="num">schema</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
    {% for r in appendix_rows %}
      <tr>
        <td class="mono">{{ r.machine_id }}</td>
        <td class="mono">{{ r.run_dir }}</td>
        <td class="mono">{{ r.db_name }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.db_bytes|fmt_bytes }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.n_results }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.n_telemetry }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.n_per_core }}</td>
        <td class="num">{{ r.schema_version }}</td>
      </tr>
    {% endfor %}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</details>

<script>
// Tiny tab-bar handler: clicking a button in .tabbar swaps the visible
// .tab-panel sharing the same data-tabgroup.
(function () {
  document.querySelectorAll(".tabbar").forEach(function (bar) {
    var group = bar.dataset.tabgroup;
    bar.addEventListener("click", function (e) {
      var btn = e.target.closest("button[data-target]");
      if (!btn) return;
      var target = btn.dataset.target;
      bar.querySelectorAll("button").forEach(function (b) {
        b.classList.toggle("active", b === btn);
      });
      document
        .querySelectorAll('.tab-panel[data-tabgroup="' + group + '"]')
        .forEach(function (p) {
          p.classList.toggle("active", p.id === target);
        });
    });
  });
})();
</script>
</body>
</html>
